		<li id="comment-40729" class="alt">
<div class="clearfix"><div class="avatarholder"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/52749528a1144074e1f03b457a95c7de?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ahousebythepark.com%2Fjournal%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2FHouse%2Fimages%2Fgravatar_default.gif%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /></div>			<div class="commentauthor">Alex says:</div></div>
			
			<p>&gt; standards, best practices v. what works</p>
<p>The only things leading to effective design are intuition and convention.</p>
<p>Intuitive designs are best, because no prior knowledge is required.</p>
<p>Conventional designs are an okay alternative, because only established, standard, prior knowledge is required.</p>
<p>Standards are important because they allow designs which will never be inherently intuitive to be usable and accessible.</p>
<p>What works should mean what is effective design: usable and accessible. In no way is anything web based extremely intuitive without standards.</p>
<p>What if every website had a different, home-grown communication protocol? (i.e. not HTTP/HTTPS)</p>
<p>Geez.</p>

			<div class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-40729" title="">#205</a> - March 24th, 2009 at 6:19 am </div>


		</li>

	
	
