<p>Games give their players meaningful choices that meaningfully impact on the world of the game. Deciding to run two miles today rather than one, or drink two liters of Coke instead of four are just choices of quantity.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Great thoughts here. Points are not very interesting on their own, and websites which use them indiscriminately to encourage loyalty are not as interesting as those which create actual games. (via <a href="http://ma.tt/2010/11/gamification/">matt</a>)</p></div></div><div><a href="http://www.mikeindustries.com/blog/archive/2010/11/gamification-vs-pointsification" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to this entry" class="noborder"><img src="http://www.mikeindustries.com/wp/wp-content/themes/Mike-Industries-Two/images/icon_comment_medium.gif" width="10" height="10" alt="" class="comment_icon" /></a><a href="http://www.mikeindustries.com/blog/archive/2010/11/gamification-vs-pointsification" title="Leave a comment">#</a></div></div></div><div class="post" id="post-5897"><div class="post_content"><div class="entry"><div class="autodiv"><img src='http://29.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lbxvdn8dev1qzvlpco1_500.jpg' alt='' width='240' height='150' /></div><div class="autodiv_double"><p><a href="http://9eyes.tumblr.com/">The Best of Google Street-View</a>: Great collection of the most striking images taken from Google’s Street-View vehicle. Lots of blurring here!</p></div></div><div><a href="http://www.mikeindustries.com/blog/archive/2010/11/the-best-of-google-street-view-great-collection-of-the-most" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to this entry" class="noborder"><img src="http://www.mikeindustries.com/wp/wp-content/themes/Mike-Industries-Two/images/icon_comment_medium.gif" width="10" height="10" alt="" class="comment_icon" /></a><a href="http://www.mikeindustries.com/blog/archive/2010/11/the-best-of-google-street-view-great-collection-of-the-most" title="Leave a comment">#</a></div></div></div><div class="post" id="post-5886"><div class="post_content"><div class="entry"><div class="autodiv"><a href="http://www.avclub.com/articles/part-3-1992-pearl-jam-the-perils-of-fame-and-the-t,47099/">Pearl Jam, the perils of fame, and the trouble with avoiding it</a>: <p><img height="124" width="240" src="http://30.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lbwbq2Ade21qzvlpco1_500.jpg"/></p>
<p>A thoughtful, but ultimately overcomplicated look at why Pearl Jam’s career arc peaked so early but has lasted so long. The simpler truth is that a lot of rock music — particularly grunge — arises not just <em>from</em> youthful adversity but <em>because</em> of it. When the hunger and adversity are gone (because you’re successful and popular), the inspiration and even ability to write that sort of music tends to disappear with it.</p>
<p>It’s also unbelievable to me that the author of this piece has not seen <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0105415/">Singles</a>. Aside from it being one of my top 5 movies of all time, I would think any lover of the early ’90s alt music scene would see it just because it exists. (via <a href="http://daringfireball.net">gruber</a>)</p>
